  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of others I care about. Growing up as an immigrant in Washington DC with parents who had only upper secondary education, I was always told to 'think outside the box' when it came to math and science. But as a woman in a male-dominated field like plumbing, I've experienced the sting of being labeled 'not a natural fit' for technical work. Stereotype threat happens when someone's identity—like being a woman, a person of color, or from a lower socioeconomic background—triggers anxiety about confirming negative stereotypes about their group. For me, it's the quiet fear that I might 'fail' in a way that reinforces the idea that women aren't good at engineering. This isn't just about individual performance; it's about systemic barriers that make people feel invisible. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of focusing on fixing the person, we need to create environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. I've noticed that when I talk to other plumbers—especially those who've come from similar backgrounds—our biggest challenge isn't the math, it's the fear of being judged for not fitting the mold. So, addressing stereotype threat means changing the culture, not just the curriculum. It means mentoring, inclusive language, and making sure that everyone knows their worth isn't tied to a single test score or a single gendered expectation. If we don't, we'll keep losing talent before they even have a chance to shine.",
